docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:4:**Goal:** Wipe Windows Server / Hyper-V, install Ubuntu 24.04 minimal server, configure for CPU-only LLM inference with dual NUMA-pinned Ollama instances.
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:47:| **Sub-NUMA Clustering (SNC)** | System BIOS > Processor Settings | **Disabled** | SNC splits each socket into 2 sub-NUMA domains (giving you 4 NUMA nodes instead of 2). This complicates memory binding for Ollama and splits your per-socket RAM in half per domain. Keep it simple: 2 nodes. |
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:141:- XFS has superior parallel I/O performance, which matters when PostgreSQL, Redis, and Ollama are all hitting the same array
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:143:- XFS has better performance for the `fallocate` patterns that Ollama uses when downloading models
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:239:If you have a GitHub account, you can import SSH keys: select "Import SSH identity" and enter your GitHub username. The installer will pull your public keys from `https://github.com/<username>.keys`. This is convenient and means you can SSH in immediately after install.
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:461:Optional: enable Tailscale SSH (so you can SSH via Tailscale identity without keys):
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:482:- `numa_balancing=0` — Disables automatic NUMA page migration. You are manually pinning Ollama instances to NUMA nodes; you do not want the kernel moving pages between nodes behind your back. This is critical for predictable inference latency.
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:483:- `transparent_hugepage=always` — Enables transparent huge pages (2MB instead of 4KB). LLM inference allocates large contiguous memory blocks; THP reduces TLB misses significantly. Some databases (PostgreSQL, Redis) recommend disabling THP, but since those are running in Docker with relatively small memory footprints compared to Ollama, the tradeoff favors THP here.
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:549:sudo mkdir -p /data/{models,postgres,redis,embeddings,logs,benchmarks,ollama-0,ollama-1}
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:604:## Part 5: Ollama Dual-Instance Setup
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:606:### 5.1 Install Ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:609:curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:612:This installs the `ollama` binary to `/usr/local/bin/ollama` and creates a systemd service. **Disable the default service** — you are going to run two custom ones:
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:615:sudo systemctl stop ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:616:sudo systemctl disable ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:619:### 5.2 Create Ollama System User (if not already created by installer)
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:621:The Ollama install script usually creates an `ollama` user. Verify:
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:624:id ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:630:sudo useradd -r -s /bin/false -m -d /usr/share/ollama ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:636:sudo chown -R ollama:ollama /data/ollama-0 /data/ollama-1
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:644:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/ollama-0.service << 'UNIT'
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:646:Description=Ollama LLM Service — NUMA Node 0
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:651:ExecStart=/usr/bin/numactl --cpunodebind=0 --membind=0 /usr/local/bin/ollama serve
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:652:User=ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:653:Group=ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:659:Environment="OLLAMA_MODELS=/data/ollama-0/models"
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:664:Environment="HOME=/data/ollama-0"
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:679:sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/ollama-1.service << 'UNIT'
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:681:Description=Ollama LLM Service — NUMA Node 1
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:686:ExecStart=/usr/bin/numactl --cpunodebind=1 --membind=1 /usr/local/bin/ollama serve
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:687:User=ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:688:Group=ollama
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:694:Environment="OLLAMA_MODELS=/data/ollama-1/models"
docs/r750-bare-metal-runbook.md:699:Environment="HOME=/data/ollama-1"
